# Land & Property Northwest

READ BRIEF.md AND STATUS.md BEFORE DOING ANYTHING. Those files are the single source of truth.

## What This Is

A paid subscription service that instantly alerts users when properties appear on the market in Northwest England. The USP is speed: subscribers find out first, before the general public. This gives investors and developers a competitive edge worth paying for.

## Priority

Revenue first. Every task should be judged by: "Does this get us closer to charging users?" The alert engine, payment flow, and subscriber dashboard are the critical path. Everything else is secondary.

## Repo Structure

- `BRIEF.md` - Product brief, USP, priorities, architecture rules, content rules. READ THIS FIRST.
- `STATUS.md` - Current project state, what is deployed, what still needs doing (prioritised).
- `plugin/lpnw-property-alerts/` - Custom WordPress plugin (the core product).
- `theme/lpnw-theme/` - GeneratePress child theme.
- `docs/` - Setup, deployment, and data source documentation.

## Tech Stack (do NOT change)

- WordPress on 20i shared hosting (PHP 8.0+)
- WooCommerce for billing (Stripe gateway)
- Mautic at marketing.land-property-northwest.co.uk for email delivery
- Server cron for scheduled data pulls
- Leaflet.js for maps
- Vanilla JS on frontend (no React, no Vue, no frameworks)

## Strict Rules

- Component-based architecture. One class per concern. No god classes.
- Follow WordPress PHP Coding Standards (WPCS)
- Prefix everything with `lpnw_`
- Use WordPress APIs only ($wpdb->prepare, wp_remote_get, wp_enqueue_scripts, etc.)
- Sanitize all input, escape all output, prepare all queries
- Never modify WordPress core
- Do NOT switch tech stacks or suggest alternatives
- Do NOT refactor working code for aesthetic reasons
- Do NOT install unapproved plugins or tools
- Do NOT write content that sounds AI-generated (no em dashes, no filler)
- Deploy via FTP to 20i hosting. See docs/DEPLOYMENT.md.

## Deployment Workaround

20i blocks automated access to wp-admin. Workaround: create temporary PHP scripts, upload via FTP, run via browser URL, then delete. The REST API at /wp-json/ IS accessible.
